&lt;p&gt;First, let&amp;rsquo;s get a working definition of &amp;ldquo;plasma&amp;rdquo;: &amp;ldquo;a quasi-neutral gas of charged and neutral particles that exhibit collective behavior.&amp;rdquo; Many of the approaches we will describe will also apply to non-neutral plasmas. Plasmas are composed of particles (electrons, ions, neutrals) which interact through electric and magnetic fields and through collisions. Therefore, the plasma &lt;em&gt;can&lt;/em&gt; be modeled as individual particles.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Particle in Cell Model</title><link>https://peppyhare.github.io/r/notes/UWAA545/03-pic-method/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://peppyhare.github.io/r/notes/UWAA545/03-pic-method/</guid><description>&lt;link rel="stylesheet" href="https://peppyhare.github.io/r/katex/katex.min.css" /&gt;
